<div class="text_div" style="padding-bottom:150px; padding-top:150px;">
  <h1>Where does the money come from?</h1>

  <!-- If artists are to make some money it has to come from somewhere! -->
  Commercial offering may vary from one DSP to the next but there exists two main mechanisms for DSPs to generate revenue: 
  <ul>
    <li> <span class="bold">Subscriptions.</span> Users of the platform pay a monthly subscription to gain access to the music on the platform. This is also known as a <em>"Premium"</em> model. </li>
    <li> <span class="bold">Ads.</span> In this scenario the users do not pay any money but instead accept to listen to and/or see ads while they use the platform. The advertisers pay the DSPs for the exposure to their customers. This is also known as a <em>"Freemium"</em> model.</li>
  </ul>


  Some DSPs like Spotify or Deezer offer both Freemium and Premium plans while some other like Apple Music or Tidal only offer Premium options.

  <!-- On legitimate question to ask at this point is: How do these sources of revenu compare to each other? Let's have a closer look on a case study using Spotify's financials for the third quarter (Q3) of 2020.   -->
</div>

<div id='container' class='container-1'>
  <div id='graph'></div>

  <div id='sections'>
    <div style="padding-top:100px">
      <h3>Spotify Case study</h3>
      Let's have a look at how these two types of revenue streams compare, using Spotify's financials for the third quarter (Q3) of 2020<sup>3</sup> as a case study.
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>User base</h3>
        First, Spotify reports that premium and (active) freemium users represent about 45% and 55% of total users, respectively. 
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Revenue per user</h3>
      Spotify reports that the monthly Average Revenue Per User (ARPU) €4.19 for premium users and €0.33 for freemium users. The ARPU tells us how much money Spotify makes per user each month, on average, globally. 
      <p class='highlight'>
      	The numbers reported mean that premium subscribers generate over 12 times more revenue than freemium users.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3> Contribution to total revenue </h3>
      To put the same numbers in a different perspective: premium subscribers represent around 45% of Spotify users and generate about 90% of the total revenue, which also means that the 55% of ad-supported users only generate about 10% of the revenue.
      <p>
      	The area of the rectangles on the graph represents the revenue.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <p>Remember that the artist royalties are a share of DSP revenue. So, everything else remaining equal, artist royalties go up if DSP revenue goes up</p>
      <p>
        <h3> How can the DSPs generate more revenue? </h3>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3> Increase ARPU </h3>
      In the case of Premium users, the ARPU is affected by the commercial offering of the DSP. For example increasing the prices of the subscription plans would increase the ARPU. 

      <p>
        The risk of a price increase is that some users may cancel their subscriptions. 
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      Conversly, promotional offers (e.g. three months free when joining) tends to decrease the ARPU. 
      <p>
        On the other hand promotional offers may help increasing the number of subscriptions, and therefore the revenue in the long run.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      In the case of Freemium users, the ARPU essentially depends on the value of the users auditive attention on the advertisement market.  

      <!-- <p>
        DSPs do not unilaterally control the advertisment market, so pushing the Freemium ARPU up is difficult.
      </p>  -->
      <!-- <p>What is for sure is that building a great product with which the users will be very engaged will help. </p> -->
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3> Converting Freemium users to Premium </h3>
      Premium users are over 10 times more profitable than Freemium users. Converting Freemium users to Premium may therefore have a huge impact on revenue. 
    </div>

    <div>
      Now you may ask: why bother with Freemium users since they generate so little revenue? 
      <p>
        Some DSPs don't and only offer Premium subscriptions. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Some do, using the Freemium tier to attract to the platform users who would not buy a subscription outright, and hopefully later "convert" some of them into Premium subscribers.
      </p>
        
    </div>

    <div style="padding-bottom:250px">
      <h3>Increase number of users</h3>
      Last but not least: increasing the total number of users on the DSP will mechanically increase revenue, by increasing the number of subscriptions and/or by increasing the size of the pool of customers available to advertisers. 
    </div>

  </div>


