<div class="text_div" style="padding-top: 200px">
	<h1>Artist Royalties Calculations</h1>
	<p>
		At this point we know that DSPs redistribute some of their revenue to the artists in the form of royalties and we know how DSPs make money. The question is now: how is the artists' royalties payments calculated? 
	</p>
</div>


<div id='container' class='container-2'>
  <div id='graph'></div>
  <div id='sections'>

    <div style="padding-top:200px">
      <h3>From DSP revenue to royalties</h3>
      First, the DSPs add up the revenue they generated.
    </div>
      
    <div>
      The dollars stack on the right represents the revenue of a DSP.
    </div>

    <div>
      This revenue is then split two ways: the DSPs keep one part for themselves and redistribute the rest of it as royalties. 

      <p>
        Although the exact numbers are confidential, the figures often quoted in the press suggest that DSPs distribute around 70% of their revenue to music right owners as royalties
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <p>
        Once the DSP share is put away, the remaining dollars stack on the right represents the royalties money pot. 
      </p>
      <p>
        The artists will receive a share of this pot.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Royalties proportional to DSP revenue</h3>
      Since the DSPs pay out a percentage of their revenue in royalties, it means that the size of the royalties money pot to share is proportional to the DSPs revenue. 

    </div>

    <div>
      In other words, more DSPs revenue means bigger royalties pie to share. 
    </div>

    <div>
      The converse is also true... Less revenue means a smaller royalties pot. 
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Revenue Pro-rata of streams</h3>
      The royalties pot is then to be split between all tracks on the platform, pro-rata of their proportion of streams. 

      <p>
    	For example, let's take a track of a given artist. If the track represents 0.1% of the total streams on the platform, it will get 0.1% of the royalties.
  	  </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      If the proportion of total streams is larger, this track will be allocated more royalties accordingly. 
      <p>
        For example if the track was to get 50% of the total streams, it would get 50% of the royalties pot.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div>
      Similarly, if the track was to get 30% of the total streams it would get 30% of the royalties pot. You get the idea. 
    </div>

    <div>
      So at the end of the day, if a track gets more streams, the artist will get a bigger royalties check, right? 

      <p>
        Not quite. The performance of all other tracks on the platform also has an influence. 
      </p> 
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Total other streams influence</h3>
      Note that the share of royalties allocated to a track depends on the <em>proportion of total streams</em>, not just on the raw number of streams that the track got.

      <p> The proportion of streams is simply the number of track streams divided by the total number of streams:
       \[Proportion  = {Track Streams \over TotalStreams}\]
   	  </p>

    </div>

    <div>
    	If the track streams remain constant and the total number of streams on the platform increases (i.e. the other tracks get more streams), the track's share of stream would be smaller. 
    </div>
    <div>
      Conversly, if the track streams remain constant and the total number of streams on the platform decreases, the track's share of stream would be larger. 
    </div>

    <div>
      In summary, every track on the DSP is entitled a share of the royalties pot that is proportional to its share of total streams. As a result, each track's royalties share depends on the number of track streams <em>and</em> on the performance of all other tracks on the platform.
    </div>

    <div>
      The better the performance of a track with respect to all other tracks on the platform, the more royalties it generates.
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Track royalties split</h3>
      Now that the track's share of royalties has been calculated, it may then be split between all parties who are entitled to a split of the royalties for this track. 
    </div>

    <div>
      <p>This is typically when the distributor and/or label may take their cut.</p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <p>
      	The distributor/label share is normally defined in the contract between the artist and the distributor/label. The numbers will vary wildly from on case to the next, depending on what agreement has been found between the parties.  
      </p>

      <p>
      	The general principle is that the distributor/label provide services to the artist and that granting them a share of royalties are one of the ways the artist can pay for these services.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      In some cases the distrubutor/label may take a relatively large share. 
      <p>This could for example be justified by the fact that the distributor provides a set of services that the artist does not pay for otherwise, or that the label has made a significant financial investment to produce the recording and is looking to recoupe its expenses from the roylalties revenue. 
      </p>
    </div>
    <div>
      In some other cases the agreement would be different and the distributor/label share will be small. 
      <p>
    	  This could for example be the case if the artist has already payed an upfront fee to the distributor or if the label only made a small financial investment in the track. 
  	  </p>
      <p>
        Some distributors even offer plans for which they take no royalties share - i.e. the artists keep 100%. 
      </p>
    </div>

    <div>
      <p class="highlight">
        The artist gets the remaining share of royalties, showed in green on the right.
      </p> 
    </div>

    <div>
      <p>Note that for simplicity we are only considering the case where there is a single artist/musician entitled royalties on the track. 
        In the general case there could be several (e.g. band members, producer) and each of them would be entitled a split of the Artists Share, 
        with the split ratios defined in a contract between all contributors. </p>
      <!-- <p>
        It is also possible that the Artist royalties share may vary over time. 
      </p> -->
    </div>

    <div>
      <h3>Why is per-stream rate misleading</h3>
      <p>
        Talking about per-stream rates being paid to the artists can be misleading because it implicitly suggests that only this rate and the number of streams impact royalties payment. 
        However, as we have seen above, the royalty payment due to the artist depends on the numer of track streams but also on many other parameters. 
      </p>
      <p>
        Per-stream rates can indeed be calculated from actual royalty payments but do not really tell the full story. 
        And most importantly they are not a good representation of royalties payment calculation. 
      </p>
    </div>

