  <h2>Making Artists a living</h2>
  <p>
    At the time of writing, only few artists make a living solely from their streaming royalties. 
    <!-- Are there levers that can be pulled to increase artists recording streaming royalties?  -->
  </p>
  <p>
    The current economics of music streaming royalties are built on a revenue share model. 
    As a result there are two ways for artists to get a bigger royalties check: get a bigger share of the pie by increasing proportion of streams of their tracks, or making the pie bigger by increasing the DSPs revenue.
    The former is every artist's career development challenge: grow their audience and grow fan engagement. The latter could be achieved by attracting more users to the music streaming platforms in general and more specifically to get more of them to pay for a subscription. There will not be more money for artists unless there is more money being spent for the consumption of their music. 
  </p>
  <p>
     Potential alternative economic models are also debated in the music industry. This debate, however, is beyond the scope of this article. The interested reader may refer to some of the references below. 
  </p>
  <p>
    Ultimately, the financial income of musical artists is made of the money the fans spend on the enjoyment of their music. 
    Keeping on supporting artists, be it by subscribing to their social media channels, getting a music streaming subscription, attending their shows or buying merch will always be the way. 
  </p>

